	Thread channel

1. Overview
	A thread channel is a mechanism for sharing
	work between multiple processor hardware threads.

	Intended for use in  user space program running
	on an AJIT multi-core and/or multi-threaded computer
	with coherent memory.


2. Details of use

     2.1 A thread channel must first be declared.
	ThreadChannel tc;

	The ThreadChannel data structure is

	typedef struct ThreadChannel__ {
		uint32_t id;
		uint32_t request_id;
		uint32_t response_id;
		void*    fn_ptr;
		void*    arg_ptr;
		// FREE, REQUESTED, COMPLETED
		int status;
	} ThreadChannel;

	The thread channel must then be initialized

	initChannel (&tc, int id_of_channel);


     2.2  A thread channel when created has status FREE.

	  A processor thread can put a job into a free
	  thread channel using 
 
	  uint32_t scheduleChannelJob (ThreadChannel* tc, void *fn_ptr, void* arg_ptr);

	  Here we are passing a function (via fn_ptr) and a single argument
          to this function (void* arg_ptr).

	  After a job is scheduled in the channel, the channel moves to status
	  REQUESTED
	
     2.3  A processor thread which is looking for work can use
          the call

	   uint32_t getChannelJob (ThreadChannel* tc, void** __fn, void** __arg);

	   to get a job in the channel tc.  If *__fn is returned as non-null,
	   then *__fn(*__arg) is called

	   After a worker thread has received a job using getChannelJob, the
	   thread channel moves to status IN_PROGRESS.

     2.4  The worker thread puts the response to the job (in *__arg above) into 
	  the thread channel..

	   uint32_t setChannelResponse (ThreadChannel* tc, void* arg_ptr);

	   After a worker thread has updated the response using setChannelResponse
	   thread channel moves to status COMPLETED.
     
     2.5  The processor who scheduled the job in the channel can read the response 
	  and use it.

	uint32_t getChannelResponse (ThreadChannel* tc, void** arg_ptr);

	  The channel moves to status FREE after the response has been read.

	The cycle can then repeat.

4.0 Example: matrix multiplication..


5.0 Notes:  
	5.1 There can be any number of thread-channels.  
		Each thread channel has a single slot in which a job can be scheduled.
